    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3243124628" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3243124628" />
    <a title="Jon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6977722-jon"><img alt="Jon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592705006p2/6977722.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3243124628?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon" href="/user/show/6977722-jon">Jon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6977722-jon?shelf=presidential-biography">presidential-biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6977722-jon?shelf=historical-biography">historical-biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3243124628" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer52929961089463195">John Meacham’s highly lauded American Lion: Andrew Jackson in the White House is a sharp and succinct account of one of America’s most consequential and influential presidents. As the title suggests, Meacham focuses on Jackson’s turbulent two-terms in the White House, utilizing a mere 50 pages on General Jackson’s prior biography. <br/><br/>Preceding the presidency, Jackson was a Tennessee frontiersman with a legal career before entering politics with brief stints in the US Congress in the House and Senat</span>
  <span id="freeText52929961089463195" style="display:none">John Meacham’s highly lauded American Lion: Andrew Jackson in the White House is a sharp and succinct account of one of America’s most consequential and influential presidents. As the title suggests, Meacham focuses on Jackson’s turbulent two-terms in the White House, utilizing a mere 50 pages on General Jackson’s prior biography. <br /><br />Preceding the presidency, Jackson was a Tennessee frontiersman with a legal career before entering politics with brief stints in the US Congress in the House and Senate. Jackson would find fame and glory in the military leading a Tennessee militia to victories in the Creek Wars of 1813 and later conquering the British in the mythic Battle of New Orleans in 1815, making Jackson a national hero.<br />Following victory in New Orleans, Jackson became an icon “among American figures to date, only George Washington enjoyed a reputation of comparable scope.” <br /><br />Leveraging his national hero status, in 1824 Jackson would make his first run for the presidency. While succeeding in winning the popular vote Jackson would not obtain a clear majority in the Electoral College. The presidency would be awarded to John Quincy Adams in the House of Representatives in what would be known as a “corrupt bargain” between Adams and House Speaker Henry Clay. Along with John C. Calhoun, these three men would remain Jackson’s most significant rivals in national politics.<br /><br />By 1828, nearly all states had essentially universal white-male suffrage. With this rise of direct democracy, Jackson would oust Adams from the White House and claim his throne as the people’s president. The Age of Jackson began, turning the presidency into a “vital center of action” forming a new Jacksonian era in American politics that would last for a generation and establish the Democratic Party.<br /><br />American Lion is a at times masterful piece of historical narrative and at times uneven. Meacham eloquently illuminates the overarching political topics of Jackson’s years in the White House, including: patronage, the National Bank veto, states’ rights and nullification, federal debt, religious influence in politics, internal improvements, and Indian removal. But given the high praise and expectations, I can’t help but feel a bit underwhelmed and it’s hard to pinpoint why. <br /><br />Meacham spends an inordinate amount of time on the “Petticoat Affair”, and while a massive scandal of the day, it’s hard to sustain great interest for the reader as to why by today’s standards. However, his account of the South Carolina nullification crisis is captivating. While Meacham does clearly point out Jackson’s many contradictions, controversies and iniquities, it’s hard to get a clear picture of how Meacham actually feels about his subject. But as he puts, “Not all great presidents were always good, and neither individuals or nations are without evil,” and perhaps that is the pertinent takeaway.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="52929961089463195" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

